==English==
===Etymology===
From Middle English, from Old English ''[[broðor|brōðor]]''. Cognates include Latin ''[[frater]]'', Greek ''[[φρατηρ]]'' (phrater), Gothic ''[[𐌱𐍂𐍉𐌸𐌰𐍂]]'' (broþar), German ''[[Bruder]]'', Russian ''[[брат]]'' (brat).

=== Noun ===
{{sb|'''brother'''
*AHD: brŭ<i>th</i>'ə(r)
*IPA: /ˈbrʌðə(r)/
*SAMPA: "brVD@(r)/
|'''[[brothers]] '''or''' [[brethren]]'''}}
#(Plural: '''brothers''') someone’s male [[sibling]]
#(Plural: '''brothers''') a male having at least one [[parent]] in common with another, see [[half-brother]], [[half-sister]]
#(Plural: '''brothers''' or '''brethren''') a male fellow member of a religious community or church
#(Plural: '''brothers''' or '''brethren''') someone who is a peer, whether male or female

====Usage note====
*The plural "brethren" tends to be used more in braoder senses than in familial ones.

